          "body": "Against the chapter's dominant register of male violence — Sheba's trumpet, Joab's sword, the battering ram against Abel's wall — comes the chapter's only named instrument of resolution: a wise woman's voice. She is unnamed; she is called *ishshah chakhamah*, a wise woman (v. 16), the same designation given the woman of Tekoa whom Joab used in chapter 14. She calls out from the city wall before it falls, requests Joab himself to approach, and speaks in two registers. First, historical: Abel has long been a place where people seek counsel and settle disputes (v. 18) — she is claiming a civic and cultural identity for her city that transcends the present military moment. Second, covenantal: she is 'peaceable and faithful in Israel' (v. 19), and what Joab is about to destroy is 'a mother in Israel' — a city that nurtures other towns and villages — and 'the inheritance of the LORD' (v. 19). She lifts the stakes from politics to theology. Joab's response is significant: he disclaims destruction (v. 20) and names his actual objective — one man (v. 21). The woman does not argue further. She promises the outcome and delivers it. Her wisdom is not merely rhetorical; it is practical and communal. She 'wisely came to all the people' (v. 22) — persuading the city rather than unilaterally acting. Sheba's head goes over the wall. The shofar blows. The siege dissolves. One voice saves a city, ends a rebellion, and restores the kingdom to David without the destruction of a single Israelite family."
