          "title": "The administrative list — order restored, Joab entrenched",
          "body": "The chapter closes with an administrative register (vv. 23-26) that mirrors the list in 2 Samuel 8:16-18. The kingdom is back in working order: Joab commands the whole army (v. 23), Benaiah commands the elite mercenary corps, Adoram oversees forced labor (a detail that will become a flashpoint under Rehoboam, 1 Kings 12:18), and the priestly and secretarial offices are filled. The list functions as a stabilizing cadence after the chaos of the chapter. But its stability is ambiguous. Joab's name heads the list — the murderer is confirmed as commander. The administrative machinery functions, but it has blood on its gears. Robert Alter (The David Story, 1999) notes that the restoration of the administrative list after a crisis is a literary signal in Samuel: the kingdom survives, order reasserts itself, but the moral wounds beneath the order are unresolved. That tension — functional power atop unresolved sin — is the condition in which David will spend the rest of his reign, and it is the condition 2 Samuel 20 leaves the reader in."
