        "excerpt": "We have no portion in David, nor do we have inheritance in the son of Jesse; every man to his tents, O Israel!",
        "body": "Sheba's cry is not political rhetoric improvised on the spot. It is a tribal manifesto drawing on deep historical resentment. The northern tribes had never been fully at peace with Judah's dominance under David; the census narrative, the border disputes, and the Absalom rebellion had all surfaced the fault line. The quarrel at the Jordan in 2 Samuel 19:41-43 — where the men of Israel accused the men of Judah of stealing the king — was the proximate provocation. Sheba simply lit the match that was already near the fuel.\n\nThe word *nachalah* (inheritance, portion) carries full covenantal weight. In the Mosaic economy, each tribe had a *nachalah* — a divinely assigned territory that was inseparable from its covenantal identity (Joshua 13-19). Sheba is saying: David has no legitimate claim over us; he is the son of Jesse of Bethlehem, a Judahite, not the king of all Israel. This is a denial of the Davidic covenant (2 Sam. 7) framed in the language of tribal land rights. The same slogan will reappear in 1 Kings 12:16 as the permanent motto of the northern secession under Jeroboam.\n\nThat 'all the men of Israel' respond instantly (v. 2) while only Judah cleaves to David (*davaq* — the covenant-loyalty verb) reveals the thinness of the restoration in chapter 19. David had been brought back not through genuine reconciliation but through a tribal dispute that left the northern men feeling cheated. A throne reassembled by competing tribal factions rather than by genuine spiritual renewal is always one trumpet blast from another crisis.\n\nTheologically, this moment is part of the long trajectory from 1 Samuel 8 — Israel's demand for a king like the nations — through the Davidic covenant of 2 Samuel 7 to the permanent split of 1 Kings 12. The Davidic kingship is God's instrument but it is administered through fallen human politics, and those politics are riddled with the fractures that sin produces. The New Testament antitype is instructive: the greater Son of David gathers a people that is not divided by tribe (Galatians 3:28; Ephesians 2:14), because His kingdom is not assembled by human political negotiation but by the Spirit.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Beliyyaal* (worthless fellow, v.1) — literally 'without profit/benefit'; the term marks its bearer as destructive rather than merely bad. *Davaq* (stayed by, v.2) — to cling, to hold fast; the same verb for the covenantal bond of marriage in Genesis 2:24 and Ruth's loyalty in Ruth 1:14. Its use here is a covenantal signal: Judah's loyalty is described in the vocabulary of covenant fidelity, not mere political calculation."
