        "excerpt": "So they were shut up until the day of their death, living as widows.",
        "body": "Verse 3 is a single verse that brings Nathan's prophecy of 2 Samuel 12:11-12 to its final, permanent expression. Nathan had announced: 'I will take your wives before your eyes and give them to your neighbor, and he will lie with them in broad daylight.' Absalom fulfilled the first half on the palace roof in 16:21-22. Now David fulfills the second half — not by remarrying the concubines (which would suggest normalcy) and not by releasing them (which might expose them to shame), but by confining them in a guarded house, provided for but untouched. The phrase *almanut chayyut* — 'widowhood of living,' or 'living widowhood' — is without parallel in biblical Hebrew. It is a constructed state of perpetual suspension: alive but as if their husbands are dead; cared for but without relational future.\n\nThe text is not interested in David's emotional state or in whether the women complained. It states the fact and moves on. This restraint is itself the moral comment. These women did nothing. They were left behind in a military retreat (15:16), violated in a political performance (16:21-22), and now confined in a juridical limbo for the rest of their lives. The innocent pay permanently for the powerful man's sin and for the rebel son's political theater. This is what Nathan meant by 'the sword shall never depart from your house' (12:10) — it does not only cut David's sons; it cuts the voiceless.\n\nFor the Christian reader, this moment points forward to the final judgment's reversal of all such injustice. The God who sees the concubines 'living as widows' is the same God who defends the widow and the orphan (Psalm 68:5; James 1:27), and the kingdom of the greater Son of David will be characterized by exactly the restoration that David's concubines never received.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Almanut chayyut* — the compound is unique in the Hebrew Bible; *almanah* (widow) normally implies the husband's death, but *chayyut* (living, of living) modifies it to indicate the husband lives but is functionally gone. The phrase captures precisely the juridical and relational no-man's-land these women inhabited."
