        "number": 4,
        "title": "The wise woman of Abel — wisdom that redirects power",
        "range": "20:14-22",
        "excerpt": "Then a wise woman called from the city, 'Hear, hear! Please tell Joab, Come here that I may speak with you.'",
        "body": "The siege of Abel Beth-maacah is the chapter's military climax, and it resolves not with a battle but with a conversation. Joab has the city surrounded, a siege ramp constructed, and the wall under active destruction (v. 15). Everything points to the city's fall. Then a woman's voice stops the machinery.\n\nShe is identified only as *ishshah chakhamah* — a wise woman (v. 16). The same epithet is given to the woman of Tekoa in 14:2. In ancient Israel, 'wise woman' was apparently a recognized role — someone known for counsel, mediation, and rhetoric. She calls from the wall, requests Joab specifically, and when he approaches, asks him to hear 'the words of your maidservant' (v. 17). Her self-designation as *amah* (maidservant) is formally deferential, but what follows is anything but submissive — it is a masterclass in covenantal argumentation.\n\nShe argues in three moves. First, historical precedent: Abel has a tradition of being a place where advice is sought and disputes resolved (v. 18). Destroying Abel is destroying a civic institution of long-standing wisdom. Second, covenantal identity: Abel is 'a mother in Israel' (v. 19) — a city that nurtures surrounding towns and villages. Its destruction is not the excision of a rebel stronghold; it is the dismemberment of the national body. Third, theological claim: Joab is seeking to destroy 'the inheritance of the LORD' (*nachalah YHWH*, v. 19) — the very word Sheba used to deny David's legitimacy (v. 1). She turns Sheba's language back against the siege. Sheba denied David any *nachalah* in Israel; she insists that Abel itself is the LORD's *nachalah*, and no one has authority to destroy it.\n\nJoab's response (vv. 20-21) is notable for its restraint and precision. He disclaims general destructive intent (*chalilah chalilah*, 'far be it, far be it' — the doubled oath of strong repudiation) and names the actual objective: one man, Sheba son of Bichri, who has 'lifted up his hand against King David' (v. 21). The woman does not need time to deliberate. She promises the outcome immediately: 'his head will be thrown to you over the wall.' She then goes to the people, persuades them, and the head comes over the wall. The shofar blows. The army disperses.\n\nTheologically, this episode illustrates the book of Proverbs' consistent conviction that wisdom (*chokmah*) is more effective than brute force. Ecclesiastes 9:13-16 comments on exactly this scenario: 'a poor wise man' saves the city by his wisdom yet is subsequently forgotten. The wise woman of Abel is also forgotten — unnamed in the text. But she saves her city, ends the rebellion, and returns Joab to Jerusalem without a single house in Abel burned. The contrast with Joab's method (sword, ambush, murder) is the chapter's moral conclusion: wisdom accomplishes what violence cannot.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Ishshah chakhamah* (wise woman, vv.16, 22) — a recognized social role in ancient Israel; see also the woman of Tekoa (14:2) and the women described in Prov. 31. *Em beyisrael* (a mother in Israel, v.19) — the same phrase used of Deborah (Judg. 5:7), a title of civic and spiritual authority. *Nachalah YHWH* (the inheritance of the LORD, v.19) — echoes Deuteronomy's theology of the land as YHWH's possession held in trust by Israel (Deut. 32:9; Ps. 68:9). *Chalilah* (far be it, v.20) — the strongest verbal disclaimer in Biblical Hebrew; used when denying something that would be sacrilegious or fundamentally wrong."
